          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Birmingham, AL 07/23/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=13823'>Edward "Special Ed" Cunningham</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=13823&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 24, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Ahhh the first tournament we&#39;ve been able to run here at Legion in quite a while.  It&#39;s not that we haven&#39;t been playing Magi, it&#39;s just so darn hard to get everyone together at once to do a tourney.<br />
<br />
Anyway, we had five players: Me playing my old Naroom deck(you can see a variation of it I posted called &quot;With Naroom no less&quot;), my roomate Blair played an out of the ordinary Arderial deck, Todd played an even weirder Arderial deck, Brett (a relatively new player for Magi Nation) and Tre (another somewhat new player) both played D&#39;Resh.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
***********  Round 1  ***********<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I pulled the by (D&#39;Oh, I hate sitting out) so I could at least watch the other games.  Blair played Todd and Tre played Brett.<br />
<br />
With two people starting Harresh (she&#39;s soooo good) you expect a close match, and this one was definately close.   Brett focused on Illusions so he followed with Hasseth and D&#39;Jarvish while Tre went the Sandsifter and removal route and used Ythra and Risha.  It was neck and neck for quite a while, with Tre maybe a little in the lead, but Sikras gave him a hard time for a while until he pulled a couple of Chill of Nights and finished it off.<br />
<br />
I didn&#39;t watch as much of Todd and Blair&#39;s game as I&#39;ve seem them play each other about a million times(that&#39;s a precise count there, one million), but I can still give you gentle readers a brief synopsis of their decks.  Blair&#39;s been running the ultimate annoying deck with Sorreah first (he can really bust up a lot of deck strategies by disrupting setup magi)  He also usually starts with the Spirit of Arderial to really prevent people from setting up their deck.  He then follows with Aula (the old one) to rebuild his hand and set up for the Adept last.  It&#39;s a pretty tough deck to beat since it has a lot of flexibility, card draw, removal and energy gain.  Todd played an Arderial Cawh control deck with all the good draw and cycling cards, Arderial&#39;s sweet control elements like Eyes of Arderial and Hand of the Sky and the good old Abwyn&#39;s Quill-Forgotten Dancer combo so you can have creatures other than the Cawh in play.  However, the tried and true deck beat out the new oddball combo deck.  Caws are just a little too hard to protect for my taste since Blair runs both the Alaban and the Storm Cloud.<br />
<br />
So it was a by for me, and wins for Blair and Tre.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
***********  Round 2  ***********<br />
<br />
<br />
Todd pulled the by, Blair played down to play Brett and I played Tre.<br />
<br />
Since I played this round I didn&#39;t see too much of Blair and Brett&#39;s game, but Blair won.  He did place top 4 at DPC Atlanta this spring, so you know he&#39;s a very good player.<br />
<br />
I played Tre.  He managed to get all 3 of his Sandsifters very quickly and I had relatively few ways of dealing with them.  I got kind of a bad draw (I made the mistake of playing Vortex of Knowlege, couldn&#39;t go first, but still drew into it in my opening hand, ouch. dead card from turn one) and lost with him still on Ythra.  If I had gotten a Warrior&#39;s Boots on Yaki I could have flip killed Ythra and still been in the game, but I was only playing one of them.  Oops.  On the whole I&#39;m just going to have to stop playing Orwin&#39;s Ring.  It&#39;s just too limiting.  Game to Tre.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
***********  Round 3  ***********<br />
<br />
<br />
Blair and Tre played for First while Todd and I played for Third.<br />
<br />
I managed to get a very good draw against Todd.  Wasperines killed Sorreah, so I could do some card drawing.  Then I got the boots on Yaki and used it to Warpath in an Ormagon... and attacked with it!  Yeah, Devastate doesn&#39;t do much against a Cawh.  By the time he got to Elios, he just didn&#39;t have enough energy.  Had he not played a Hand of the Sky he could have played a Cahw, Healing Light and used Storm of Fishes to get rid of my Rayje&#39;s Belts in hand.  But he couldn&#39;t so I just overwhelmed him with energy.  Third place to me.<br />
<br />
Tre went first against Blair and dropped a Sandsifter and another Oracle.  Since I hadn&#39;t seen the latest Rules update that had come out the day before I was under the impression that the Tre could not sacrifice an Oracle that was already being discarded to save a Sandsifter, so Blair flipped Sorreah and Started with the Cataclysm and basically kept the advantage after that.  Slops to me for not being up to date on the rules.  I think Blair uses Sandswirl too so he could have just pulled both the Swirl and the Cat and still been good.  He never even got to the Adept, so I guess he probably still would have won even if I hadn&#39;t made the wrong ruling in his favor.<br />
<br />
I had three months worth of Animite Prizes, plus we had some packs from the entry fees, so everyone walked away with something and a good time was had by all.  Except maybe Todd, who won&#39;t be ranked #1 in the state by tomorrow. <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/treports/treports.php?id=4553&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
